A '''double-take''' is a [[nonverbal communication]] in which a second look is taken at something with a marked physical reaction such as shock, astonishment, or amazement.<ref name=charney>{{cite book|last1=Charney|first1=Maurice|title=Comedy: A Geographic and Historical Guide, Volume 2|date=2005|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=9780313327155|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=or6G-rTUs44C&pg=PA613&lpg=PA613&dq=Double-take+comedy&source=bl&ots=aEj65c7ZhF&sig=kiN4c0dhMO9sWFDPSfz-deW-Diw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CFEQ6AEwCWoVChMI8KjT0Z-_yAIVSeqACh3UNgE3#v=onepage&q=Double-take%20comedy&f=false|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref> In theatrical terms, a 'take' is a physical reaction to seeing something.<ref name=tdf>{{cite web|title=Double Take|url=http://dictionary.tdf.org/double-take/|website=Theatre Dictionary|publisher=THEATRE DEVELOPMENT FUND|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref> Comic characters often perform a double take because of the absurd world in which they are performing, and their audiences are often in a similar position when they have had an instant to reflect on a comic performance.<ref name=lang>{{cite book|last1=Hutchinson|first1=Peter|title=Landmarks in German Comedy|date=2006|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=9783039101856|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=aYlZjsv116QC&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=Double-take+comedy&source=bl&ots=NFSM9lqx5g&sig=lgZe-h62IBAzMHdZTDBsR9JijaM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAzgKahUKEwjf-5zhqr_IAhVDHT4KHZDIBhs#v=onepage&q=Double-take%20comedy&f=false|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref> With correct timing a double-take seldom fails to get a laugh.<ref name=harrison>{{cite book|last1=Harrison|first1=Martin|title=The Language of Theatre|date=1998|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=9780878300877|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ofbGhtZyiHwC&pg=PA84&lpg=PA84&dq=first+double-take+used+in+theatre&source=bl&ots=N0yOZ9l0tq&sig=f7GCFPXL10zH1WDmuXNjTkP6DUs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAmoVChMI5fz_tbC_yAIVBtKACh1mWw4s#v=onepage&q=first%20double-take%20used%20in%20theatre&f=false|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref> The double-take has probably been in the comedians repertoire for centuries and the term has been in general use since at least the 1940s.<ref name=harrison />

